Standard deviation (SD)
Standard deviation is the square root of the variance. This takes into account that that the variance includes the square of the difference between the individual values and the mean:
Population Variance \[
\sigma^2 = \frac{\sum((x_i- \bar{x}{})\color{Red}{^2})} {N}
\]
Population SD \[
\sigma^2 = \sqrt\frac{\sum((x_i- \bar{x}{})\color{Red}{^2})} {N}
\]
Sample Variance \[
S^2 = \frac{\sum((x_i- \bar{x}{} )\color{red}{^2})} {N - 1}
\] Sample SD \[
S^2 = \sqrt\frac{\sum((x_i- \bar{x}{} )\color{red}{^2})} {N - 1}
\]
